{"key":"post-15312574","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15312574</id>\n<content>Rotating is always good, or having it in front of a window with a light on the other side.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Pins usually form on the opposite side of the substrate from the light.&amp;nbsp; It's the mushroom mycelium which absorbs and uses the light during this phase, so I speculate this is a survival technique that evolved to prevent the mushrooms themselves from being scorched by the sun.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bear in mind, if you have a ton of pins, expect many of them to abort.&amp;nbsp; This is normal, so don't try to fix what isn't broken when you see it.&amp;nbsp; A substrate can only support so many fruits, so the mycelium, not you, will decide which ones to let grow and which ones to abort.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15312604</next>\n<prev>15312549</prev>\n<first>15312337</first>\n<last>15312604</last>\n<when>1320247076</when>\n<utime>11/02/11 06:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}